# greedy_vs_naive.tas — Meshing-strategy visual regression.
#
# Purpose: capture an identical scene through the naive + greedy meshers and
# confirm they render visually identical frames. The greedy-mode shader uses
# `fract(uv)` for texel tiling so merged rects repeat the per-block noise
# pattern, matching what the naive mesher produces exactly.
#
# Compare:
#   --meshing=naive   → baseline, one quad per visible block face
#   --meshing=greedy  → default, coplanar same-material/lighting faces merged
#
# The test intentionally mixes three conditions on a flatland world:
#   1. Flat grass plains  — greedy merges the entire chunk-top to 1 quad.
#   2. A small dug pit    — introduces per-vertex skylight gradient that
#                           *breaks* merging (every wall cell has distinct
#                           skylight), so greedy must emit multiple faces.
#   3. Oblique camera pan — exposes many faces at non-perpendicular angles
#                           where any bilinear interpolation mismatch would
#                           become visible.
#
# Usage (from utils/swindowzig):
#   zig build native -Dexample=voxel
#   ./zig-out/bin/voxel --world=flatland --aa=none --meshing=naive \
#     --tas examples/voxel/tests/greedy_vs_naive.tas \
#     --dump-frame=/tmp/greedy_vs_naive_naive.ppm
#   ./zig-out/bin/voxel --world=flatland --aa=none --meshing=greedy \
#     --tas examples/voxel/tests/greedy_vs_naive.tas \
#     --dump-frame=/tmp/greedy_vs_naive_greedy.ppm
#
# Or just run the wrapper:
#   ./examples/voxel/tests/greedy_vs_naive.sh
#
# Tick numbering is relative to the first post-loading tick.

# --- Capture mouse ---
1 mouse_down left
2 mouse_up left

# --- Look down so the flat grass surface fills most of the view. ---
3 mouse_move 0 120

# --- Dig four blocks deep into the flat plain. ---
5  mouse_down left
6  mouse_up left
9  mouse_down left
10 mouse_up left
13 mouse_down left
14 mouse_up left
17 mouse_down left
18 mouse_up left

# --- Tilt up slightly so the hole + surrounding plain are both in frame. ---
22 mouse_move 0 -30

# --- Pan horizontally so the camera angle is oblique (tests interpolation). ---
24 mouse_move 8 0
25 mouse_move 8 0
26 mouse_move 8 0
27 mouse_move 8 0
28 mouse_move 8 0

# Hold steady so --dump-frame lands on a stable view.
33 mouse_move 0 0
